commentText: I have been living in Munich for the last five years and feel here so unsafe regarding housing. I was nearly homeless four years ago when my landlady gave me only four weeks notice of rental contract termination. It was horrible... nobody even wanted to rent me a WG room because I am PhD student with ridiculously low-income and short-term working contracts with no guarantees of extension. Only few days before my rental contract ended I managed to get a place to stay which is in horrible conditions - in the cellar, no sunlight, full of mold, horrible plumping issues, constant backflow of sewage water in the shower cabin which of course gives horrible smell. And of course in the middle of nowhere, super far from the city center and from my university. Of course my landlords violate many laws in here. Of course they knew I am a  poor Eastern European PhD student living from paycheck to paycheck in this expensive city all by myself, and I cannot afford hiring a lawyer against them. It was the biggest mistake of my life to start PhD in Munich... Luckily this nightmare is coming to the end, hopefully I will get my degree in summer and next month I am finally leaving Germany for good! :)

Taking courses at German universities, even short-term Weiterbildung programs, can really help. commentText: Just one thing to add: childcare is not free in every German federal state. I am German and I have not only lived in Germany, but also in 2 other countries, but at no point have I ever expected to be accommodated in English or in German. The idea did not even occur in my mind. In fact I had learned the languages before going there and dedicated a lot of time and money to it so I could actually achieve a certificated C1 level for one country and a C2 for the other.  I don't think you absolutely need that I believe you will probably get by with a B2 level, but at the least you should have a B1 level.  It is one thing if you fled from another country, then you really have no chance to prepare for this, but if you actively choose a country, no matter which one, you absolutely do have the chance to prepare and you absolutely should!  Personally I believe that speaking the language also will let you have a completely different experience and make life, social interactions and everything so much easier. I would not underestimate the power of language.

commentText: I'm an engineer from Romania working and living in Germany for more than 8 years now. When I came over I did so with a direct contract, though, I did invest time in learning the language at least to a B2 level when I considered looking for a job here. And, while I have 8 years here, my language skills are far from what I want them to be, so I still, periodically, do language courses. Since then, with COVID and the drop in German Automotive industry, my company closed but my CEO collected a few of us and started a new one. So, in my 8 years, I collected unemployment for only 1 month. Switching out of the Automotive industry (where my main experience was) took about 1.5 - 2 years of constant learning, interviewing and self-correcting. I had a lot of interviews where I got to the end stage of the process but it took time, attention to what I could improve after each interview and a significant amount of energy and research. So, work through it, I'm not saying its 100% going to happen, but chances for skilled workers, with German language skills (even poor ones), are quite good in my experience. As for German bureaucracy, I come from Romania :) Germany does have more bureaucracy but I find it's functional and quite efficient. The social and taxation systems would probably not work as well without it. However, I do think a lot is over-regulated here and this is consistent with the opinion of my German colleagues :).  What feel is missing and is becoming problematic is digitalization and quality of services. Most, from state provided services (finance, medical, city offices), to private, service oriented, businesses like banks and telecommunication are outdated, overpriced and of mediocre quality.  All in, Germany is, for me, a lot better than Romania, the caveat being: your family and long-time friends are now a long way away. This is not a small factor in your quality of life. There are a lot of things to improve, but this is as much a chance as an issue, since you can be part of improving some aspects and helping your adoptive country.

videoTitle: The HARD Truth About Jobs and Money in Germany
videoDescription: From MBA Student to Real Estate Investor: 15 Years of Expat Life in Germany ‚û°Ô∏è     Meet Anshul Garg, an Indian expat ...
commentText: Very interesting to learn about the experiences of an expat in Germany. I am a German and lived in the USA for 12 years, but did not work there and my husband is American. Still....the experience is similar. You always experience a culture shock, even when you come from a similar one. Anyway...to fully enjoy the new culture you have to learn everything about it and you have to adjust. The new culture will not adjust to you. Learning the native language is the most important thing. Germans expect you to speak German, in France they expect you to speak French etc. At work you might get away with English, but when you want your electricity to be cut on or whatever you need to speak the native language of the country you live in. Just because English is the widely spread language you cannot expect that everybody can speak two languages. In the US nobody would expect that amybody knows the Italian or German language. About the handshake....Take my word for it...when you grow up with it, it is a normal thing and the way we say hello. And yes, when you shake anybody's hand you look in the eyes of that person. Anything else would not make any sense. And I agree...before anybody moves to another country they should learn about the culture beforehand. What you do inside your home is up to you, but when you step outside please show respect to the country you live in. When my girlfriend came for a visit to the USA she wanted to sunbath top less at the community pool. It took me a long time to convince her that she cannot to this in the USA. To her it was so normal that she could not get her head wrapped around it that she could end up in jail in the US for doing so. It is really important to know about the culture if you plan to live there. It also helps to talk to natives and show interest. They love to learn about your culture also.

commentText: A great honest take on business life in Germany. I compare and contrast this to people who have spend the same amount of time in USA or Australia and feel more at home there. The other major point of assimilation is how we have been open to the culture and relationships in the adopted Country. Did we marry there, did we raise our kids to think like a local or think like an Indian, do you enjoy and partake in local sports, or stick to only cricket. Do you volunteer your time for the good of local people or work for agencies that help out locals? How have you inserted yourself into becoming one with your neighborhood town/city? These things make a huge difference in the way you assimilate into a new culture OR you can remain an expat and take your wealth and go back to India in retirement.  Good thought provoking video!

commentText: The guy is definitely very knowledgeable about Germany but there is a point i would like to make:  Yes house prices have risen dramatically in the decade  until 2023. Since then prices are stagnant.  Now that decade was an exception caused by extraordinarily low interest rates that effectively induced a real estate bubble.  The next decade is very unlikely to see the same growth in prices, so basically up to 2023 it was really hard to lose money with real estate. In the years to come it will be hard to make money with real estate, obviously not impossible but real hard.

commentText: The likelihood of coming to Germany as a student and securing a job afterward is quite limited because Germany generally encourages students to immigrate temporarily and then return to their home countries after graduation. Unlike the US, UK, and other countries where students often stay and work permanently, this is not typically the case in Germany. While it's possible to find lower-level jobs that don't match your qualifications simply because you're fluent in German, this isn't a sustainable long-term strategy. High taxes and living costs mean that you probably won't become wealthy; instead, you'll live an average life. Additionally, there's intense competition, and employers tend to favor native Germans over migrants.   German employers also usually prefer candidates from prestigious US and British universities like Yale or Cambridge over student immigrants with a university degree from Germany. This is a fact. They often welcome international students primarily for economic reasons, not necessarily to provide more employment opportunities. I know an American who studied here,  became fluent in German (C1 level), speaking almost like a native, but she told me most employers rejected her in favor of native Germans. She eventually returned to the US.   So, believing that studying in Germany will guarantee a job afterward is an illusion. There are already highly qualified refugees from other countries who are unemployed here. Many YouTube channels don't have a thorough understanding of the German system; while some are relatively trustworthy, they still lack complete knowledge and experience. Comparatively, this YouTube is genuine, although the guy didn't cover some other facts, which I can understand may be due to a lack of knowledge of the German system.

videoTitle: IT Jobs In Germany 2025 (Real Experience)
videoDescription: The true reality of IT jobs in Germany 2025, coming from a person that lives here and work as Software Developer.
commentText: As a Security Analyst / Incident Responder, I can say the market is (almost) dead - at least if you want a salary matching your experience. The IT sector plummeted in 2024/2025, with most jobs being ghost listings. 100% remote is rare unless it‚Äôs a foreign company with a German branch. Local firms demand fluent German and in-office presence, often 3 days/week. Big cities offer slightly higher pay, but cost of living kills your net income. If you have a 3h commute - your problem, unpaid. Certs? Mostly on your own time and dime. Customers want to outsource responsibility, not collaborate, while MSSPs overpromise services they can‚Äôt deliver. If you‚Äôre OK earning 10‚Äì15k less than you're worth, Germany‚Äôs IT sector is waiting. Otherwise, consider Austria or Switzerland. Also, if you're single, expect 38‚Äì40% of your 40‚Äì65k yearly gross salary to vanish through taxes and insurance. You're also expected to already know everything - onboarding is just a theoretical concept.

videoDescription: The true reality of IT jobs in Germany 2025, coming from a person that lives here and work as Software Developer.
commentText: First mistake is to think EU salaries are similar to US salaries or that salary negotiation works the same in EU than US. Salaries in EU are kind of fixed no matter the company you will earn mostly the same in regards on your role level. Second mistake is to think english is enough to work in any country this is very wrong and that applies not only to Germany but all other EU countries. If you really want to thrive in a non-english speaking country you will need to have at least C1 level. Third mistake is to think in terms of amount and not purchasing power and cost of living in regards of salaries. I lived in Dusseldorf and currenlty living in Spain. f.i. earning 65k in Spain has the same purchasing power as earning 85k in Germany. This is a very common mistake people do. I prefer Spain over Germany 1000% but I have the advantage that I speak Spanish and German fluently so I can choose. Europe is the best option if you are looking for a good life and very good work-life balance plus job labor laws that protects you from the company bs. if you are looking to work 24/7 because you are an entreprenur with the shark mindset and want to own your company and be able to abuse the system because you have a lot of money then move to the US evil corp system.

videoTitle: Getting an IT Job in Germany (Salaries and Opportunities)
videoDescription: Best way to learn German as a beginner: https://youtu.be/s63TwG3XfSA #germany #workingermany #lifeingermany.
commentText: This information sounds not in an inch close to reality. I'm a Senior Software Engineer with Bachelor's degree in CS and 12+ years of experience living in Germany and after being laid off early this year I am not able to find a job in any city for 4 months now. There are offices of Google, Microsoft and other big tech companies yes, but all of them except Amazon are barely hiring here. Other international tech companies like Salesforce, IBM, Oracle, Snowflake, Datadog, Hubspot are not hiring here at all. When it comes to salaries, somehow being a senior I ended up earning the same amount as the upper boundary of an early career software developer's salary you named. I've been asking more, but some recruiters straight out say that they are targeting for far less, since the SWE job market here is severely oversaturated. One of the recruiters told me that the job opening I applied for got 300+ applications. Please do your research more deeply next time

commentText: Experience is the key to success in IT. And a broad knowledge base. Going too specialized can make it hard to find a new job. No AI will find an issue or fix it if it goes totally out of whack. 3 examples: - a bank always had a network outage at noon when the staff was having break time. After a longer research, I figured out the cleaning team was pulling a certain plug in the building when vacuum cleaning, and took out the network while cleaning. - Intermittent non reproducible network outages. Reason: the electrical motors of an elevator interrupted the entire network as the cables were installed in the elevator shaft. - Once I had a customer PC that only powered up, when a *hammer* was lying on the casing. TAKE THAT AI!!!

commentText: Good points but some corrections and points to consider to get true full picture: 1. The comparison between India and Germany for unemployment is not accurate. One is because both are percentage and hence doesnt depend on the size of population. Second, the true unemployment rate in India cannot be measured because of unorganized labour and underemployed labour which constitutes more than 70% of indian economy.  2. You mentioned "most of the employees getting laid off" are expats or foreigners - is there any data to back this up? I am not fully sure why this would be the case and find no reason for companies here to selectively choose foreigners and fire them.  3. In terms of automotive companies laying off people, its only half the picture what you stated. For example, VW decided to layoff 5000 employees by 2027. However, because labour unions are strong, the way "layoff" happens is by identifying people nearing retirement (arnd 65) and asking them to quit before "unofficial" retirment age of 67 in exchange of an year's salary. In a way this is layoff, but really different from what happens in other parts. In companies with strong labour unions, despite the news of layoffs, in reality most layoffs are "voluntary" in nature in exchange of almost 6-8 months of salary in addition to the unemployment benefit of 60% wage they would receive.  All other points mentioned are correct
